Delete a Data Model Object and Remove Field Mappings

You can delete a data model object (DMO) and remove data lake object (DLO) field mappings in the data mapping canvas.

REQUIRED EDITIONS
Available in: All Editions supported by Data Cloud. See Data Cloud edition availability.

You can delete the DMO only if it’s a custom object. You can’t delete a standard object. Standard objects can exist in the org in an unmapped state. Custom objects can’t exist without any field mappings.

The trash icon (Remove Mappings option) enables you to remove all field mappings to the DMO or to delete the DMO. The changes take effect immediately.

The Remove Mappings option isn’t available or fails when:

The field mapping referential integrity check fails. When you try to remove a field mapping, Data Cloud performs a referential integrity check to ensure that downstream dependencies such as Identity Resolution, Calculated Insights, Segments etc. aren’t adversely impacted if the field mappings are removed. If the referential integrity check fails for any of the DMO fields that are currently mapped, you can’t remove the field mapping.
TIP If you want to change the field mapping from one DLO field to another field in the same DLO, the referential integrity check also prevents you from changing the mapping. To circumvent this check, you can set up a temporary field mapping to a different DLO, delete the field mapping you no longer want, and then add the new field mapping. Remember to delete the temporary mapping.
At least one of the fields in the DMO has a mapping from just one DLO. When you remove that field mapping, the DMO field has no more field mappings. Because a custom DMO can’t exist without field mappings, the only valid option is to delete the DMO.
The DLO is being used in the source priority of identity resolution reconciliation rules. You can’t remove the field mapping until you remove the dependencies.
IMPORTANT This dependency isn’t visible in the error dialog, it must be manually confirmed through the Identity Resolution reconciliation rules configuration page.
The field corresponding to the mapping that you’re trying to remove is used on a Data Cloud Lightning page. First, remove the field from the Data Cloud page.
IMPORTANT This dependency isn’t visible in the error dialog, it must be manually confirmed through the Lightning page configuration tool.

The Delete Object option removes field mappings from all DLOs that are mapped to the DMO, and then deletes the DMO. The delete object option isn’t available if the DMO has downstream dependencies, such as Identity Resolution, Segments, Calculated Insights, and Activations. You must remove all the dependencies before you can delete the object.

When at least one of the DMO fields has a mapping from just one DLO, the Remove Mappings button isn’t available. However, you can delete the object entirely.

Object Dependencies

When you attempt to delete a DMO with dependencies, Data Cloud lists the dependencies that must be removed before the DMO can be deleted. This referential integrity check is performed individually for each DMO field rather than just the DMO. You can also view which data streams are using the DMO, but data streams don’t prevent deleting an object. After reviewing the dependency list, if you choose to disassociate the current DLO from its mapping to the DMO and not delete the object, click Remove Mappings instead of Delete Object.

To delete a Profile DMO, first delete all segments related to the DMO. Then, delete the associated Segment Membership DMOs created by Data Cloud. To delete the associated Segment Member DMOs, navigate to the Data Models tab and change the List Views from Mapped to All. Search for the name of the Profile DMO that you want to delete. Then, delete both of the associated Segment Membership DMOs. Finally, delete the Profile DMO.
